<DocsLayout title="Getting started" description="Install etmc, add a relay, and play.">
  <h2>Install</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Install <a href="https://fabricmc.net/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Fabric Loader</a> (or NeoForge / Forge)
      for your Minecraft version — Fabric covers 1.17.1 through 26.x, NeoForge 1.20.6 and 1.21.10, Forge 1.21.10.</li>
    <li>Drop the etmc jar into your <code>mods/</code> folder; on Fabric also add
      <a href="https://modrinth.com/mod/fabric-api" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Fabric API</a>.</li>
    <li>Launch the game — Java 17 for 1.17.1 – 1.20.1, Java 21 for 1.20.6 – 1.21.10, Java 25 for 26.x.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Open the menu</h2>
  <p>Press <span class="kbd">G</span> (rebindable under <em>Controls → Misc</em>) or run <code>/etmc menu</code>.</p>

  <h2>Add a relay</h2>
  <p>
    etmc ships no public relay — you provide one. In <strong>Settings</strong>, add an EasyTier node, for example
    <code>tcp://my.relay:11010</code>. The relay coordinates peer discovery and NAT traversal. You can run your own
    EasyTier public node or use one you trust.
  </p>
  <div class="note">No relay = no connections. This is the one piece of setup etmc can't do for you.</div>

  <h2>Play</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Host this world</strong> → pick a network name (+ optional secret) → share the join code.</li>
    <li>Friends pick <strong>Join with a code</strong> and paste it.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>See <a href="/docs/hosting">Hosting</a> and <a href="/docs/joining">Joining</a> for details.</p>
</DocsLayout>
